04553nam a22007095i 9781501744563DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191993nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017445637 a10.7591/97815017445632doi  a(DE-B1597)534092  a(OCoLC)1129184121  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBD241b.K74 1993eb 7aSOC0050002bisacsh04a121/.682221 aKrausz, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRightness and Reasons :bInterpretation in Cultural Practices /cMichael Krausz. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b2 b&w illustrations, 9 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Interpretation in Cultural Practices -- t1. Rightness and Reasons in Musical lntrepretation -- t2. Cultural Practices and the Ideals of Interpretation: Singularism and Multiplism -- t3. Imputational Interpretation in Art, Poetry, Persons, and Cultures -- t4. Imputation and the Comparison of Interpretations -- tPart II. Interpretation without Ontology -- t5. Objects-of- Interpretation and Their Indeterminacy -- t6. Historical Interpretation without Ontology -- t7. Praxial Ideality without Ontological Realism -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: From an Interview with a Luo Medicineman -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMust there be a single right interpretation of a particular cultural entity? In his book Michael Krausz considers this question in such representative cultural practices as music, visual art, history, and cross-cultural understanding.Krausz advances two main theses. First, he argues, the notion that there must be a single right interpretation in cultural practices—the "singularist" view—is misplaced. Without acceding to an interpretive anarchism, he embraces the "multiplist" view that cultural practices characteristically allow a multiplicity of ideally admissible interpretations. In his discussion Krausz critically outlines the maneuvers available to both singularists and multiplists.Second, Krausz notes that singularists characteristically construe their objects-of-interpretation along realist lines, and multiplists along constructionist lines.But, he argues, these associations are not necessary: the singularist condition is not guaranteed by realism, nor the multiplist by constructionism. Krausz holds that the question of interpretive ideals is detachable from the dispute between realists and constructionists.Addressing topics of intense concern within mainstream analytic philosophy and in many other areas of cultural investigation, Rightness and Reasons will berewarding reading for aestheticians, musicologists, art historians, literary theorists, historiographers, and anthropologists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAesthetics. 0aHermeneutics. 0aOntology. 4aAnthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Customs & Traditions.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150174456340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501744563423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501744563.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK